1
00:00:30,980 --> 00:00:33,100
<i>At the outbreak of World War II</i>

2
00:00:33,500 --> 00:00:37,300
<i>Germany increased its U-boat
production by 1000%.</i>

3
00:00:37,500 --> 00:00:40,580
<i>Mass producing 17 new U-boats a month.</i>

4
00:00:41,980 --> 00:00:44,900
<i>Hitler knew the key to winning
the war in Europe...</i>

5
00:00:45,100 --> 00:00:46,780
<i>was to control the Atlantic.</i>

6
00:00:49,700 --> 00:00:51,700
<i>And control it, they would.</i>

7
00:01:01,180 --> 00:01:05,300
<i>By the end of 1942,
German U-boats working in groups...</i>

8
00:01:05,340 --> 00:01:09,500
<i>known as "wolfpacks",
sunk over 1,000 allied ships.</i>

9
00:01:14,900 --> 00:01:18,180
<i>This success gave Germany
a decisive advantage.</i>

10
00:01:22,700 --> 00:01:25,980
<i>They were winning the war,
and if this trend continued...</i>

11
00:01:26,100 --> 00:01:27,980
<i>all of Europe would fall.</i>

12
00:01:28,100 --> 00:01:29,500
IN ENEMY HANDS

13
00:01:31,380 --> 00:01:36,300
<i>In January 1943, President Roosevelt,
and Prime Minister Churchill...</i>

14
00:01:36,580 --> 00:01:39,980
<i>declared that stopping the U-boats
would be their top priority.</i>

15
00:01:42,700 --> 00:01:46,780
<i>With the US fully committed to the war,
and new advances in technology...</i>

16
00:01:46,900 --> 00:01:48,900
<i>the allies strike back.</i>

17
00:01:50,700 --> 00:01:53,980
<i>After losing an average
of only five U-Boats a month...</i>

18
00:01:54,100 --> 00:01:58,100
<i>Germany suffers its greatest losses
in what would be known as Black May.</i>

19
00:02:02,100 --> 00:02:05,700
<i>That month, allies sink
and destroy 41 U-Boats.</i>

20
00:02:06,900 --> 00:02:10,100
<i>8 out of every 10 U-boat sailors died.</i>

21
00:02:13,700 --> 00:02:18,180
<i>The rain of the wolfpack was
rapidly drawing to a close.</i>

22
00:02:20,780 --> 00:02:23,580
Dept. of the Navy
June 3, 1943

23
00:02:24,380 --> 00:02:25,580
I've known you your whole life.

24
00:02:25,620 --> 00:02:27,700
I'm not going to embarrass you
with the details.

25
00:02:28,300 --> 00:02:29,700
Your father was a good man.

26
00:02:29,780 --> 00:02:31,180
A great soldier.

27
00:02:31,380 --> 00:02:32,900
Thank you, Sir.

28
00:02:33,300 --> 00:02:36,580
It's out of respect for him that
I just assume you didn't do this.

29
00:02:41,300 --> 00:02:43,100
We're not here to chase ghosts.

30
00:02:43,780 --> 00:02:45,580
Our job is to pursue an enemy...

31
00:02:45,780 --> 00:02:46,780
and defeat it.

32
00:02:48,380 --> 00:02:49,780
You certain that's what you wanna do?

33
00:02:50,100 --> 00:02:51,300
Absolutely.

34
00:02:54,300 --> 00:02:55,380
When do you ship out?

35
00:02:55,500 --> 00:02:56,500
In two weeks.

36
00:02:56,580 --> 00:02:57,900
Monday after next...

37
00:02:57,980 --> 00:02:59,700
we'll be ready.

38
00:02:59,980 --> 00:03:01,380
Have you met your C.O.B. yet?

39
00:03:01,420 --> 00:03:04,100
No Sir, Nate Travers, not yet.

40
00:03:04,300 --> 00:03:06,980
Nathan Travers, a good man.

41
00:03:08,180 --> 00:03:11,180
You might actually learn something from him
if you're interested in that sort of thing.

42
00:03:15,500 --> 00:03:17,980
- Give 'em hell, Commander.
- Oh, I plan to, Sir.

43
00:03:18,500 --> 00:03:19,980
- That's an order.
- Yes, Sir.

44
00:03:26,300 --> 00:03:29,180
I'm just waiting for some things
hanging on the line to dry.

45
00:03:29,780 --> 00:03:32,180
And your mom wants you
to call her before you go.

46
00:03:32,580 --> 00:03:35,700
Don't go without calling her because I'm
the one who's gonna have to deal with it...

47
00:03:35,980 --> 00:03:37,700
everyday until you get back.

48
00:03:38,580 --> 00:03:40,380
I love her, but she's your mother.

49
00:03:40,580 --> 00:03:41,700
You deal with her.

50
00:03:42,300 --> 00:03:43,700
I'm gonna take this.

51
00:03:45,500 --> 00:03:46,780
I'm taking this with me.

52
00:03:48,500 --> 00:03:50,380
I'll stick it right above my bunk.

53
00:03:51,180 --> 00:03:53,300
It'll be the last thing
I see when I go to bed...

54
00:03:54,580 --> 00:03:56,500
and the first thing
I see when I wake.

55
00:03:57,700 --> 00:04:00,300
Oh, dammit.
Why do you go and do that?

56
00:04:00,380 --> 00:04:02,380
- What?
- You know what.

57
00:04:02,580 --> 00:04:05,700
Now you got me started,
and I can't stop once I get started.

58
00:04:06,380 --> 00:04:07,180
Sorry.

59
00:04:07,980 --> 00:04:09,180
You're not sorry.

60
00:04:10,580 --> 00:04:11,900
I love you.

61
00:04:14,900 --> 00:04:16,980
- Promise me something Nate Travers.
- Anything.

62
00:04:20,180 --> 00:04:23,500
Promise me you won't get yourself
killed trying to be a hero.

63
00:04:24,700 --> 00:04:26,300
You think you can get rid
of me that easily?

64
00:04:26,380 --> 00:04:27,500
No, I'm serious.

65
00:04:28,980 --> 00:04:30,500
Honey, don't start that.

66
00:04:30,980 --> 00:04:33,180
Promise me you'll come home.

67
00:04:33,900 --> 00:04:35,100
I promise.

68
00:04:35,980 --> 00:04:37,700
Swear it.

69
00:04:40,180 --> 00:04:43,100
I swear... I'll come home to you.

70
00:04:44,300 --> 00:04:45,100
Okay.

71
00:05:01,500 --> 00:05:04,380
Two Months later
August 2nd 1943

72
00:05:04,980 --> 00:05:07,780
Mid-Atlantic Convoy Route
600 miles off the U.S. Coast

73
00:05:35,900 --> 00:05:39,500
- Heinrich!
- Turn off the air-intake!

74
00:05:43,380 --> 00:05:49,500
- Stubborn bastards, those Americans.
- All ahead, 15 degrees starboard.

75
00:06:02,580 --> 00:06:06,100
- They're leaving.
- They're leaving.

76
00:06:06,300 --> 00:06:13,300
Periscope depth. We'll teach them
who the stubborn ones are.

77
00:06:24,380 --> 00:06:31,100
- 286 degrees, 15 knots.
- Distance: 2,700 meters.

78
00:06:32,300 --> 00:06:35,700
Ready tubes 3 and 4.

79
00:06:44,300 --> 00:06:45,380
Ready.

80
00:06:45,580 --> 00:06:49,500
- 112 degrees.
- Torpedo ready?

81
00:06:49,700 --> 00:06:51,700
3 and 4 ready.

82
00:06:54,500 --> 00:06:55,500
Ready.

83
00:06:58,180 --> 00:06:59,780
Fire.

84
00:07:20,500 --> 00:07:21,900
Yes! We got her!

85
00:07:24,580 --> 00:07:25,700
We got her!

86
00:07:25,900 --> 00:07:32,300
- A good yankee is a dead yankee.
- We dive.

87
00:07:42,980 --> 00:07:46,380
U.S.S. Swordfish
Balao-Class Attack Submarine

88
00:08:08,500 --> 00:08:10,780
- All ahead two thirds.
- All ahead two thirds.

89
00:08:11,500 --> 00:08:12,780
Make ready to dive.

90
00:08:12,820 --> 00:08:14,180
Make ready to dive.

91
00:08:14,300 --> 00:08:16,300
Shut 'em down, we're switching
to battery power!

92
00:08:16,340 --> 00:08:18,780
Come on! Move it! Let's go!

93
00:08:18,980 --> 00:08:21,500
Knock it off, come on!
And get your hands off your pecker!

94
00:08:21,540 --> 00:08:23,500
- Giddy up!
- Yeah, yeah!

95
00:08:23,900 --> 00:08:26,900
- Green board, pressure in the boat.
- Take her to 60.

96
00:08:27,500 --> 00:08:29,500
Take her to 60, five degree down-angle.

97
00:08:29,540 --> 00:08:31,500
60 feet, five degree down-angle, aye.

98
00:08:40,180 --> 00:08:41,180
Fuck!

99
00:08:52,700 --> 00:08:53,580
60 feet, Sir.

100
00:08:54,700 --> 00:08:56,580
- Zero bubble?
- Zero bubble, Sir.

101
00:08:57,180 --> 00:08:58,700
Zero bubble at 60, Sir.

102
00:08:58,780 --> 00:08:59,580
Scope up.

103
00:08:59,780 --> 00:09:00,900
Scope up!

104
00:09:03,580 --> 00:09:04,700
Time?

105
00:09:04,900 --> 00:09:05,900
64 seconds.

106
00:09:06,700 --> 00:09:07,980
64 seconds.

107
00:09:08,980 --> 00:09:10,300
64 seconds.

108
00:09:11,700 --> 00:09:13,380
Prepare to surface, exercise complete.

109
00:09:13,500 --> 00:09:15,180
Prepare to surface, exercise complete.

110
00:09:15,700 --> 00:09:16,900
Chief, in my quarters.

111
00:09:17,780 --> 00:09:19,100
Periscope going down!

112
00:09:22,380 --> 00:09:23,580
Not again!

113
00:09:25,180 --> 00:09:26,900
Maybe I should just go for a swim.

114
00:09:26,980 --> 00:09:27,980
Can I join you?

115
00:09:28,180 --> 00:09:29,580
- Now, Chief.
- Be right there, Sir.

116
00:09:31,500 --> 00:09:33,500
You look like crap,
you should see the medic.

117
00:09:33,700 --> 00:09:35,180
There's a lot of things I should do.

118
00:09:35,700 --> 00:09:41,300
Three months. Three months in the water
and the men become compleasant and sloppy.

119
00:09:41,580 --> 00:09:43,100
If you were in my shoes,
would that trouble you?

120
00:09:43,380 --> 00:09:44,700
Yes, Sir.

121
00:09:44,980 --> 00:09:47,300
Today's dive time was 64 seconds.

122
00:09:47,780 --> 00:09:49,700
3 days ago it was 58 seconds.

123
00:09:50,380 --> 00:09:51,780
6 seconds, Chief.

124
00:09:51,900 --> 00:09:52,980
We're in the Atlantic now...

125
00:09:53,100 --> 00:09:55,380
we can't afford to give the
Germans a six second advantage.

126
00:09:55,700 --> 00:09:56,580
I'll speak to the men.

127
00:09:58,580 --> 00:10:00,100
See that you do.

128
00:10:03,580 --> 00:10:04,500
Chief.

129
00:10:05,380 --> 00:10:07,100
You may have more experience...

130
00:10:07,380 --> 00:10:10,780
but I've been preparing for this for
a long time and I do know what I'm doing.

131
00:10:11,380 --> 00:10:12,700
I don't doubt that, Sir.

132
00:10:13,380 --> 00:10:14,980
So, what's on your mind, Chief?
Let's have it.

133
00:10:17,780 --> 00:10:19,500
I was thinking about
the men's morale.

134
00:10:19,700 --> 00:10:21,700
They're frustrated by these
constant exercises...

135
00:10:21,740 --> 00:10:23,780
and it's clearly not helping
their performance.

136
00:10:25,380 --> 00:10:28,500
What is it? You and the men are
disappointed we haven't seen any action?

137
00:10:29,180 --> 00:10:31,580
No, it's not that.

138
00:10:31,780 --> 00:10:34,380
Then what is it, Chief?
What is it?

139
00:10:34,780 --> 00:10:36,380
I was thinking...

140
00:10:36,500 --> 00:10:38,100
to keep spirits up,
maybe we could...

141
00:10:38,180 --> 00:10:40,300
give 'em a little more latitude...

142
00:10:40,580 --> 00:10:41,900
little less exercise.

143
00:10:43,500 --> 00:10:45,100
That's not your decision.

144
00:10:45,700 --> 00:10:47,100
And I've made mine.

145
00:10:47,180 --> 00:10:49,180
The crew's performance is
not what it needs to be.

146
00:10:49,580 --> 00:10:51,500
And the drills will
continue per my orders.

147
00:10:51,980 --> 00:10:53,100
Understood?

148
00:10:53,500 --> 00:10:54,380
Aye, Sir.

149
00:10:54,980 --> 00:10:55,980
Is that all?

150
00:10:57,380 --> 00:10:58,700
Yeah, that's all.

151
00:10:59,380 --> 00:11:00,300
You're dismissed.

152
00:11:06,980 --> 00:11:12,980
- How is Heinrich?
- Concussion. He'll be okay.

153
00:11:13,180 --> 00:11:16,100
Good, I'll check in on him later.

154
00:11:20,180 --> 00:11:24,100
- Good move.
- You always win anyway.

155
00:11:25,180 --> 00:11:29,100
- Do you know what your problem is?
- My queen is in a bad position.

156
00:11:29,380 --> 00:11:31,900
You always underestimate yourself.

157
00:11:32,100 --> 00:11:36,780
You should have been a commander yourself,
instead of hanging around with me.

158
00:11:40,100 --> 00:11:43,900
I thought that you would be more cheerful,
after we sunk that cruiser.

159
00:11:47,100 --> 00:11:52,700
We sink one, they sink 30.
We're lucky that the torpedo exploded.

160
00:11:53,700 --> 00:11:58,700
- The Americans joined the war.
- It didn't go so well last night.

161
00:11:58,980 --> 00:12:04,100
It'll all be better soon.
With a little luck...

162
00:12:04,300 --> 00:12:08,300
With a little luck,
we'll make it home in one piece.

163
00:12:30,580 --> 00:12:34,900
- What is it, Bauer?
- Look at this.

164
00:12:44,700 --> 00:12:47,780
Always when you least expect it.

165
00:12:50,180 --> 00:12:53,980
- How many moves do I have left?
- Two.

166
00:12:54,180 --> 00:12:56,700
Check...

167
00:12:58,180 --> 00:12:59,500
...mate.

168
00:12:59,700 --> 00:13:05,100
Good, I hate chess.
I get worse in every new move.

169
00:13:06,380 --> 00:13:12,100
- Sorry to disturb you, Captain. Mr. Cremer.
- We're finished.

170
00:13:15,300 --> 00:13:19,300
We got a message...
from home.

171
00:13:20,180 --> 00:13:21,780
Give it to me.

172
00:13:36,100 --> 00:13:39,900
Jonas... what does it say?

173
00:13:44,700 --> 00:13:47,500
I need a moment alone.

174
00:13:55,700 --> 00:13:59,500
They bombed Hamburg. The school his
daughters attend is completely destroyed.

175
00:13:59,700 --> 00:14:02,700
No survivors.

176
00:14:14,380 --> 00:14:15,700
All right, don't be stingy.

177
00:14:16,700 --> 00:14:17,780
Thanks.

178
00:14:17,980 --> 00:14:20,780
How many dress rehearsals is that?
Twenty seven, twenty eight maybe?

179
00:14:20,980 --> 00:14:23,700
I don't know... I don't care.

180
00:14:24,180 --> 00:14:25,700
I figured as much from you.

181
00:14:25,900 --> 00:14:26,700
I mean...

182
00:14:26,740 --> 00:14:27,900
It's not like we've
never done it before?

183
00:14:28,100 --> 00:14:29,980
I just don't get why he
doesn't find some krautsto pester...

184
00:14:30,020 --> 00:14:31,900
instead of jerking
our chains and fuckin' us.

185
00:14:31,980 --> 00:14:33,500
Yeah, I mean, what's he trying to prove?

186
00:14:33,580 --> 00:14:36,300
The least he could do is, whenever
it's not real, he could tell us.

187
00:14:36,380 --> 00:14:37,700
So we don't shit
our pants everytime.

188
00:14:38,300 --> 00:14:41,300
That would explain the complaints
I've been getting from laundry services.

189
00:14:45,380 --> 00:14:46,180
Chief.

190
00:14:48,180 --> 00:14:51,100
The reason we've conducted twenty
seven exercises Mr. Miller...

191
00:14:51,300 --> 00:14:54,780
is for you to become so accustomed
to your task, so masterful in your skills...

192
00:14:54,900 --> 00:14:58,900
that you do not shit yourself when
this boat comes under attack.

193
00:14:59,900 --> 00:15:01,100
I understand, Chief.

194
00:15:03,300 --> 00:15:07,380
Wanna talk some trash? Save it for
those nazi sons of bitches...

195
00:15:07,420 --> 00:15:10,380
crawling up and down our East Coast
looking to blow us out of the water.

196
00:15:12,500 --> 00:15:13,580
Anyone seen the XO?

197
00:15:13,900 --> 00:15:16,700
Oh, yeah. I think I saw
him go into the head, Chief.

198
00:15:38,500 --> 00:15:40,380
You're all right in there, Sir?

199
00:15:41,180 --> 00:15:42,100
Fine, Chief.

200
00:15:42,180 --> 00:15:43,580
I'll be out in a minute.

201
00:15:45,500 --> 00:15:46,940
U 281
Two days later

202
00:15:46,980 --> 00:15:48,180
290 miles northeast of Bermuda

203
00:15:56,580 --> 00:15:59,380
British Merchant Vessel Achilles

204
00:16:03,900 --> 00:16:05,780
Torpedoes... Fire.

205
00:16:06,500 --> 00:16:08,300
How do you lose an entire convoy?

206
00:16:11,700 --> 00:16:13,580
Increase speed to 18 knots.

207
00:16:22,500 --> 00:16:24,580
The Achille's last
radio contact, here.

208
00:16:24,780 --> 00:16:27,580
That's where the closest allied
vessel had been ordered to take a look.

209
00:16:27,900 --> 00:16:31,100
There's been no report of U-Boat
activity in that area for several weeks.

210
00:16:31,180 --> 00:16:32,700
That does not mean
they're not there.

211
00:16:33,300 --> 00:16:34,380
Chief...

212
00:16:34,500 --> 00:16:35,700
no drill this time.

213
00:16:35,900 --> 00:16:37,180
I'll inform the men.

214
00:16:37,580 --> 00:16:39,580
Confirm coordinates, let CINCLANT
know that we're on our way.

215
00:16:39,620 --> 00:16:40,580
Aye, Captain.

216
00:16:57,980 --> 00:17:00,900
We have to surface.

217
00:17:04,380 --> 00:17:07,980
Jonas, it's night.
We have to surface.

218
00:17:09,300 --> 00:17:13,100
- Yes, prepare for surfacing.
- Ready for surfacing.

219
00:17:13,700 --> 00:17:14,780
Who's in there?

220
00:17:16,500 --> 00:17:18,500
I've been waiting for too long.

221
00:17:20,500 --> 00:17:21,900
Hey, open up.

222
00:17:23,900 --> 00:17:25,900
- Oh, shit!
- Who is it?

223
00:17:26,300 --> 00:17:28,300
The XO, let's get him
to the medic. Come on.

224
00:17:34,500 --> 00:17:35,580
Flu?

225
00:17:36,300 --> 00:17:37,380
Not sure.

226
00:17:37,580 --> 00:17:38,980
Could be a reaction
to something he ate.

227
00:17:39,500 --> 00:17:40,700
How long have you
been feeling like this?

228
00:17:41,180 --> 00:17:43,380
A week maybe, since Panama.

229
00:17:43,700 --> 00:17:45,900
Hey, Chief. The Captain needs you.

230
00:17:45,980 --> 00:17:47,380
I think it's important.

231
00:17:47,900 --> 00:17:49,380
I need to come too.

232
00:17:49,780 --> 00:17:52,380
- You're not going anywhere.
- You wish you could order me around.

233
00:17:52,580 --> 00:17:53,500
I can.

234
00:17:54,580 --> 00:17:56,780
Keep the liquids coming,
and let me know of any changes.

235
00:17:56,900 --> 00:17:58,100
Yes, Sir.

236
00:17:58,500 --> 00:18:00,100
There's Cooper at your service.

237
00:18:06,980 --> 00:18:09,380
We need to keep him here,
away from the rest of the crew.

238
00:18:09,500 --> 00:18:12,900
Until I have a chance to check on the others
to see if they have any of the same symptoms.

239
00:18:13,380 --> 00:18:14,500
Is that serious?

240
00:18:15,500 --> 00:18:16,900
It could be meningococcus.

241
00:18:17,580 --> 00:18:18,780
English?

242
00:18:18,820 --> 00:18:21,300
It's a form of meningitis,
it's highly contagious...

243
00:18:21,380 --> 00:18:23,700
and in some cases it can be fatal.

244
00:18:31,500 --> 00:18:34,580
We couldn't stop the bleeding
in the brain.

245
00:18:36,180 --> 00:18:39,180
How old was he? 18?

246
00:18:41,700 --> 00:18:44,900
Heinrich wanted to show
what he could do.

247
00:18:45,100 --> 00:18:47,300
From the first day.

248
00:18:47,580 --> 00:18:52,500
You couldn't do anything.
You couldn't stop it.

249
00:18:53,380 --> 00:18:56,100
No...

250
00:18:56,300 --> 00:18:59,700
That's the problem.

251
00:19:06,500 --> 00:19:07,700
Anything?

252
00:19:07,900 --> 00:19:08,700
No, Sir.

253
00:19:11,100 --> 00:19:13,700
Chief, glad you could join us.
